Topic: credit score classification¶

INTRODUCTION:¶

In this case study, we explore the application of machine learning techniques to predict credict scores based on a

comprehensive dataset containing various customer attributes and financial information.

The dataset includes features such as customer demographics, income, loan, details, payment behavior, and credit utilization.

By utilizing this data, we aim to develop a machine learning model capable of accurately predicting credit scores for individuals.

The results of this study can assist financial institutions in automating the credit assessment process and improving lending decisions.

OBJECTIVE:¶

The objective is to do apply to python and Exploratory Data Analytics and apply to testing of hypothesis and Machine learning technique to influnce by the in credit score standard or good or poor.

DataSet Description:¶

ID: Unique identifier for each entry

Customer_ID: Unique identifier for each customer

Month: Month of the data entry

Name: Name of the customer (missing values present)

Age: Age of the customer

SSN: Social Security Number of the customer

Occupation: Occupation of the customer

Annual_Income: Annual income of the customer

Monthly_Inhand_Salary: Monthly in-hand salary of the customer (missing values present)

Num_Bank_Accounts: Number of bank accounts held by the customer

Num_Credit_Card: Number of credit cards held by the customer

Interest_Rate: Interest rate associated with the customer

Num_of_Loan: Number of loans taken by the customer

Type_of_Loan: Type of loan taken by the customer (missing values present)

Delay_from_due_date: Delay in payment from the due date

Num_of_Delayed_Payment: Number of delayed payments made by the customer (missing values present)

Changed_Credit_Limit: Indicator if the credit limit has changed

Num_Credit_Inquiries: Number of credit inquiries made by the customer

Credit_Mix: Credit mix of the customer

Outstanding_Debt: Outstanding debt of the customer

Credit_Utilization_Ratio: Credit utilization ratio of the customer

Credit_History_Age: Age of credit history for the customer (missing values present)

Payment_of_Min_Amount: Payment behavior of the customer

Total_EMI_per_month: Total EMI (Equated Monthly Installment) paid by the customer

Amount_invested_monthly: Monthly amount invested by the customer (missing values present)

Payment_Behaviour: Payment behavior of the customer

Monthly_Balance: Monthly balance of the customer (missing values present)

Credit_Score: Credit score of the customer

Target variable¶

Credit_Score: standard or poor or good

INSIGHTS DATA: Number of Attribute:23 Target Attribute:Credit_Score

def Month_Converter(x):
    if pd.notnull(x):
        num1 = int(x.split(' ')[0])
        num2 = int(x.split(' ')[3])
      
        return (num1*12)+num2
    else:
        return x

import re
In [37]:
def get_Diff_Values_Colum(df_column, diff_value=[], sep=',', replace=''):   
    column = df_column.dropna()
    for i in column:
        if sep not in i and i not in diff_value:
            diff_value.append(i)
        else:
            for data in map(lambda x:x.strip(), re.sub(replace, '', i).split(sep)):
                if not data in diff_value:
                    diff_value.append(data)
    return dict(enumerate(sorted(diff_value)))

# Reassign and Show Function
def Object_NaN_Values_Reassign_Group_Mode(df, groupby, column, inplace=True):      
    # Assigning Wrong values Make Simple Function
    def make_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace=True):
        # Assign None to np.NaN
        if df[column].isin([None]).sum():
            df[column][df[column].isin([None])] = np.NaN
            
        # fill with local mode
        result = df.groupby(groupby)[column].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(stats.mode(x)[0][0]))

        # inplace
        if inplace:
            df[column]=result
        else:
            return result
    
    # Run      
    if inplace:  
        # Before Assigning NaN values   
        if df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).index.isna().sum():
            x = df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).loc[[np.NaN]]
            print(f'\nBefore Assigning: {column}:', f'have {x.values[0]} NaN Values', end='\n')
            
        a = df.groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list) 
        print(f'\nBefore Assigning Example {column}:\n', *a.head().values, sep='\n', end='\n')
        
        # Assigning
        make_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace)
        
        # After Assigning NaN values
        if df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).index.isna().sum():
            y = df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).loc[[np.NaN]]
            print(f'\nBefore Assigning: {column}:', f'have {y.values[0]} NaN Values', end='\n')
            
        b = df.groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list)
        print(f'\nAfter Assigning Example {column}:\n', *b.head().values, sep='\n', end='\n')
    else:   
        # Show
        return make_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace)

# Reassign Wrong Values and Show Function
def Numeric_Wrong_Values_Reassign_Group_Min_Max(df, groupby, column, inplace=True):      
    import scipy.stats as stats 

    # Identify Wrong values Range
    def get_group_min_max(df, groupby, column):            
        cur = df[df[column].notna()].groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list)
        x, y = cur.apply(lambda x: stats.mode(x)).apply([min, max])
        return x[0][0], y[0][0]
    
    # Assigning Wrong values
    def make_group_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace=True):
        df_dropped = df[df[column].notna()].groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list)
        x, y = df_dropped.apply(lambda x: stats.mode(x)).apply([min, max])
        mini, maxi = x[0][0], y[0][0]

        # assign Wrong Values to NaN
        col = df[column].apply(lambda x: np.NaN if ((x<mini)|(x>maxi)) else x)

        # fill with local mode
        mode_by_group = df.groupby(groupby)[column].transform(lambda x: x.mode()[0] if not x.mode().empty else np.NaN)
        result = col.fillna(mode_by_group)

        # inplace
        if inplace:
            df[column]=result
        else:
            return result
        
    
    # Run      
    if inplace:   
        # Before Assigning NaN values   
        if df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).index.isna().sum():
            x = df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).loc[[np.NaN]]
            print(f'\nBefore Assigning: {column}:', f'have {x.values[0]} NaN Values', end='\n')
            
        print("\nExisting Min, Max Values:", df[column].apply([min, max]), sep='\n', end='\n')       
        mini, maxi = get_group_min_max(df, groupby, column)        
        print(f"\nGroupby by {groupby}'s Actual min, max Values:", f'min:\t{mini},\nmax:\t{ maxi}', sep='\n', end='\n')        
        
        a = df.groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list) 
        print(f'\nBefore Assigning Example {column}:\n', *a.head().values, sep='\n', end='\n')
        
        # Assigning
        make_group_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace)
        
        # After Assigning NaN values
        if df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).index.isna().sum():
            y = df[column].value_counts(dropna=False).loc[[np.NaN]]
            print(f'\nBefore Assigning: {column}:', f'have {y.values[0]} NaN Values', end='\n')
        
        b = df.groupby(groupby)[column].apply(list)
        print(f'\nAfter Assigning Example {column}:\n', *b.head().values, sep='\n', end='\n')
    else:   
        # Show
        return make_group_NaN_and_fill_mode(df, groupby, column, inplace)

In [99]:
def missingval(df):
    missvalcount = df.isnull().sum()
    missvalpercent = df.isnull().sum()/df.shape[0]*100
    newdf = pd.concat([missvalcount,missvalpercent],axis=1)
    newdf1 = newdf.rename(columns={0:'missvalcount',1:'missval %'})
    newdf1 =newdf1[newdf1['missvalcount']!=0].sort_values(by='missvalcount',ascending=False)
    return newdf1

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

# Split the data into training and validation sets
x_train, x_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Initialize the list for storing OOB scores and model hyperparameters
scores = []
hyperparameters = []

# Iterate over different values of n_estimators
for i in range(50, 100, 10):
    # Create and fit the Random Forest classifier
    bgc = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=i, oob_score=True)
    bgc.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Perform cross-validation to evaluate the model
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(bgc, x_val, y_val, cv=5)
    mean_cv_score = cv_scores.mean()
    scores.append(mean_cv_score)
    hyperparameters.append(i)

    # Print the cross-validated score
    print(f"For n_estimators={i}, cross-validated score is {mean_cv_score}")

# Find the best hyperparameter value
best_index = scores.index(max(scores))
best_n_estimators = hyperparameters[best_index]
print(f"Best n_estimators: {best_n_estimators}")

# Train the final model using the best hyperparameter value
final_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=best_n_estimators)
final_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the final model on the test set
ypred = final_model.predict(xtest)
accuracy = accuracy_score(ytest, ypred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")
print(classification_report(ytest, ypred))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from xgboost import XGBClassifier

# Define the machine learning algorithms
models = {
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(),
    'K Nearest Neighbors': KNeighborsClassifier(),
    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(),
    'Naive Bayes': GaussianNB(),
    'AdaBoost': AdaBoostClassifier(),
    'Gradient Boosting': GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    'XGBoost': XGBClassifier()
}

# Train and evaluate each model
accuracy_scores = []
for model_name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    accuracy = model.score(xtest, ytest)
    accuracy_scores.append(accuracy)

# Create a bar plot of the accuracy scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(models.keys(), accuracy_scores)
plt.xlabel('Machine Learning Models')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy Score')
plt.title('Comparison of Accuracy Scores for Different Models')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
